[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] A **domain-specific language** (**DSL**) is a computer language specialized to a specific application domain.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] This is in contrast to a general-purpose language (GPL), which is broadly applicable across domains.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] There are a wide variety of DSLs, ranging from widely used languages for common domains, such as HTML for web pages, down to languages used by only one or a few pieces of software, such as MUSH soft code.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] DSLs can be further subdivided by the kind of language, and include domain-specific *markup* languages, domain-specific *modeling* languages (more generally, specification languages), and domain-specific *programming* languages.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] Special-purpose computer languages have always existed in the computer age, but the term "domain-specific language" has become more popular due to the rise of domain-specific modeling.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] Simpler DSLs, specifically ones used by a single application, are sometimes informally called **mini-languages**.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] For example, Perl was originally developed as a text-processing and glue language, for the same domain as AWK and shell scripts, but was mostly used as a general-purpose programming language later on.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] In contrast, PostScript is a Turing-complete language, and in principle can be used for any task, but in practice is narrowly used as a page description language.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] The design and use of appropriate DSLs is a key part of domain engineering, by using a language suitable to the domain at hand – this may consist of using an existing DSL or GPL, or developing a new DSL.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] Language-oriented programming considers the creation of special-purpose languages for expressing problems as standard part of the problem-solving process.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] Pragmatically, a DSL may be specialized to a specific problem domain, a specific problem representation technique, a specific solution technique, or other aspects of a domain.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] A domain-specific language is created specifically to solve problems in a specific domain and is not intended to be able to solve problems outside of it (although that may be technically possible).
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] In contrast, general-purpose languages are created to solve problems in many domains.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] A domain-specific language is somewhere between a tiny programming language and a scripting language, and is often used in a way analogous to a programming library.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] The boundaries between these concepts are quite blurry, much like the boundary between scripting languages and general-purpose languages.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] Domain-specific languages are languages (or often, declared syntaxes or grammars) with very specific goals in design and implementation.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] A domain-specific language can be one of a visual diagramming language, such as those created by the Generic Eclipse Modeling System, programmatic abstractions, such as the Eclipse Modeling Framework, or textual languages.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] For instance, the command line utility grep has a regular expression syntax which matches patterns in lines of text.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] The sed utility defines a syntax for matching and replacing regular expressions.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] Often, these tiny languages can be used together inside a shell to perform more complex programming tasks.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] The line between domain-specific languages and scripting languages is somewhat blurred, but domain-specific languages often lack low-level functions for file system access, interprocess control, and other functions that characterize full-featured programming languages, scripting or otherwise.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] Further blurring this line, many domain-specific languages have exposed APIs, and can be accessed from other programming languages without breaking the flow of execution or calling a separate process, and can thus operate as programming libraries.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] Some domain-specific languages expand over time to include full-featured programming tools, which further complicates the question of whether a language is domain-specific or not.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] In model-driven engineering, many examples of domain-specific languages may be found like Object Constraint Language (OCL), a language for decorating models with assertions or Query/View/Transformation (QVT), a domain-specific transformation language.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] However, languages like Unified Modeling Language (UML) are typically general-purpose modeling languages.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] To summarize, an analogy is useful: a *very little language* is like a knife, which can be used in thousands of different ways, from cutting food to self-defense.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] A *domain-specific language* is like an electric drill: it is a powerful tool with a wide variety of uses, but a specific context, namely, making holes in things.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] A *general purpose language* is a complete workbench, with a variety of tools intended for performing a variety of tasks.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] Domain-specific languages should be used by programmers who, looking at their current workbench, realize they need a better drill and find that a given domain-specific language provides exactly that.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] DSLs implemented via an independent interpreter or compiler are termed *external domain specific languages*.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] A separate category termed *embedded (or internal) domain specific languages* are typically implemented within a host language as a library and tend to be limited to the syntax of the host language, though this depends on host language abilities.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] Adopting a domain-specific language approach to software engineering involves both risks and opportunities.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] The well-designed domain-specific language manages to find the proper balance between these.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] GML is a domain-specific language used by GameMaker Studio designed to help novice programmers learn the fundamentals of coding more easily.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] It functions as a blend of several languages, including Delphi, C++, and BASIC.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] Most GML functions, once compiled, call runtime functions written in the specific language of the target platform; consequently, their final implementation remains hidden from the user.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] The language's primary goal is to lower the barrier to entry for game development.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] The GameMaker runtime, which manages the main game loop and handles function implementation, allows a simple game to use only a few lines of code instead of thousands.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] ColdFusion's associated scripting language is another example of a domain-specific language for data-driven websites.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] The language is used to weave together languages and services such as Java, .NET, C++, SMS, email, email servers, http, ftp, exchange, directory services, and file systems for use in websites.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] The ColdFusion Markup Language (CFML) includes a set of tags that can be used in ColdFusion pages to interact with data sources, manipulate data, and display output.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] CFML tag syntax is similar to HTML element syntax.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] Although the FilterMeister language reproduces a significant portion of the C language and function library, it contains only those features which can be used within the context of Photoshop plug-ins and adds a number of specific features only useful in this specific domain.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] The *Template* feature of MediaWiki is an embedded domain-specific language whose fundamental purpose is to support the creation of page templates and the transclusion (inclusion by reference) of MediaWiki pages into other MediaWiki pages.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] There has been much interest in domain-specific languages to improve the productivity and quality of software engineering.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] Domain-specific language could possibly provide a robust set of tools for efficient software engineering.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] Such tools are beginning to make their way into the development of critical software systems.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] The Software Cost Reduction Toolkit is an example of this.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] A newer development is language-oriented programming, an integrated software engineering methodology based mainly on creating, optimizing, and using domain-specific languages.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] Complementing language-oriented programming, and all other forms of domain-specific languages, are the class of compiler writing tools called metacompilers.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] Such compiler is useful for generating parsers and code generators for domain-specific languages, and a metacompiler compiles a domain-specific metalanguage specifically designed for the domain of metaprogramming.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] Besides parsing domain-specific languages, metacompilers are useful for generating a wide range of software engineering and analysis tools.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] The meta-compiler methodology is often found in program transformation systems.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] Metacompilers that played a significant role in both computer science and the computer industry include META II, and its descendant TreeMeta.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] Unreal and Unreal Tournament unveiled a language named UnrealScript.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] This allowed rapid development of modifications relative to the competitor Quake (using the Id Tech 2 engine).
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] The Id Tech engine used standard C code meaning C had to be learned and properly applied, while UnrealScript was optimized for ease of use and efficiency.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] Similarly, more recent games have introduced their own specific languages for development.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] One more common example is Lua for scripting.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] Various business rules engines have been developed for automating policy and business rules used in both government and private industry.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] ILOG, Oracle Policy Automation, DTRules, Drools and others provide support for DSLs aimed to support various problem domains.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] DTRules goes so far as to define an interface for the use of multiple DSLs within a rule set.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] The purpose of business rules engines is to define a representation of business logic in as human-readable fashion as possible.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] This allows both subject-matter experts and developers to work with and understand the same representation of the business logic.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] Most rules engines provide both an approach to simplifying the control structures for business logic (for example, using declarative rules or decision tables) coupled with alternatives to programming syntax in favor of DSLs.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] Statistical modelers have developed domain-specific languages such as R (an implementation of the S language), Bugs, Jags, and Stan.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] These languages provide a syntax for describing a Bayesian model and generate a method for solving it using simulation.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] Generate object handling and services based on an Interface Description Language for a domain-specific language such as JavaScript for web applications, HTML for documentation, C++ for high-performance code, etc.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] This is done by cross-language frameworks such as Apache Thrift or Google Protocol Buffers.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] Gherkin is a language designed to define test cases to check the behavior of software, without specifying how that behavior is implemented.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] It is meant to be read and used by non-technical users using a natural language syntax and a line-oriented design.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] The tests defined with Gherkin must then be implemented in a general programming language.
[src:scotty-haskell/domain-specific-language] Then, the steps in a Gherkin program acts as a syntax for method invocation accessible to non-developers.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] Haskell's semantics are historically based on those of the Miranda programming language, which served to focus the efforts of the initial Haskell working group.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] The last formal specification of the language was made in July 2010, while the development of GHC continues to expand Haskell via language extensions.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] Haskell is used in academia and industry.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] As of May 2021, Haskell was the 28th most popular programming language by Google searches for tutorials, and made up less than 1% of active users on the GitHub source code repository.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] After the release of Miranda by Research Software Ltd. in 1985, interest in lazy functional languages grew.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] By 1987, more than a dozen non-strict, purely functional programming languages existed.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] Miranda was the most widely used, but it was proprietary software.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] At the conference on Functional Programming Languages and Computer Architecture (FPCA '87) in Portland, Oregon, there was a strong consensus that a committee be formed to define an open standard for such languages.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] The committee's purpose was to consolidate existing functional languages into a common one to serve as a basis for future research in functional-language design.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] Haskell was developed by a committee, attempting to bring together off-the-shelf solutions where possible.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] Type classes were first proposed by Philip Wadler and Stephen Blott to address the ad hoc handling of equality types and arithmetic overloading in languages at the time.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] In early versions of Haskell up until and including version 1.2, user interaction and input/output (IO) were handled by both streams-based and continuation-based mechanisms, which were widely considered unsatisfactory.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] In version 1.3, monadic IO was introduced, along with the generalisation of type classes to higher kinds (type constructors).
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] Along with "do notation", which provides syntactic sugar for the `Monad` type class, this gave Haskell an effect system that maintained referential transparency and was convenient.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] Another notable change in early versions was the moving of the "sequential evaluation" operation `seq` (which creates a data dependency between values, and is used in lazy languages to avoid excessive memory consumption) from a type class to a standard function to make refactoring more practical.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] The first version of Haskell ("Haskell 1.0") was defined in 1990.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] The committee's efforts resulted in a series of language definitions (1.0, 1.1, 1.2, 1.3, and 1.4).
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] In late 1997, the series culminated in *Haskell 98*, intended to specify a stable, minimal, portable version of the language and an accompanying standard library for teaching, and as a base for future extensions.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] The committee expressly welcomed creating extensions and variants of Haskell 98 via adding and incorporating experimental features.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] In February 1999, the Haskell 98 language standard was originally published as *The Haskell 98 Report*.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] In January 2003, a revised version was published as *Haskell 98 Language and Libraries: The Revised Report*.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] The language continues to evolve rapidly, with the Glasgow Haskell Compiler (GHC) implementation representing the current *de facto* standard.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] In early 2006, the process of defining a successor to the Haskell 98 standard, informally named *Haskell Prime*, began.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] This was intended to be an ongoing incremental process to revise the language definition, producing a new revision up to once per year.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] The first revision, named *Haskell 2010*, was announced in November 2009 and published in July 2010.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] Haskell 2010 added several well-used and uncontroversial features previously enabled via compiler-specific flags.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] The next formal specification had been planned for 2020.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] On 29 October 2021, with GHC version 9.2.1, the GHC2021 extension was released.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] While this is not a formal language spec, it combines several stable, widely used GHC extensions to Haskell 2010.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] Haskell features lazy evaluation, lambda expressions, pattern matching, list comprehension, type classes and type polymorphism.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] It is a purely functional programming language, which means that functions generally have no side effects.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] A distinct construct exists to represent side effects, orthogonal to the type of functions.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] A pure function can return a side effect that is subsequently executed, modeling the impure functions of other languages.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] Haskell has a strong, static type system based on Hindley–Milner type inference.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] Its principal innovation in this area is type classes, originally conceived as a principled way to add overloading to the language, but since finding many more uses.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] The construct that represents side effects is an example of a monad: a general framework which can model various computations such as error handling, nondeterminism, parsing and software transactional memory.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] They are defined as ordinary datatypes, but Haskell provides some syntactic sugar for their use.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] Haskell has an open, published specification, and multiple implementations exist.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] Its main implementation, the Glasgow Haskell Compiler (GHC), is both an interpreter and native-code compiler that runs on most platforms.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] GHC is noted for its rich type system incorporating recent innovations such as generalized algebraic data types and type families.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] The Computer Language Benchmarks Game also highlights its high-performance implementation of concurrency and parallelism.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] An active, growing community exists around the language, and more than 5,400 third-party open-source libraries and tools are available in the online package repository *Hackage*.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] Using Haskell's Fixed-point combinator allows this function to be written without any explicit recursion.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] As the *Integer* type has arbitrary-precision, this code will compute values such as `factorial 100000` (a 456,574-digit number), with no loss of precision.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] All listed implementations are distributed under open source licenses.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] Jan-Willem Maessen, in 2002, and Simon Peyton Jones, in 2003, discussed problems associated with lazy evaluation while also acknowledging the theoretical motives for it.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] In addition to purely practical considerations such as improved performance, they note that lazy evaluation makes it more difficult for programmers to reason about the performance of their code (particularly its space use).
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] In particular it disables type classes by default.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] Ben Lippmeier designed Disciple as a strict-by-default (lazy by explicit annotation) dialect of Haskell with a type-and-effect system, to address Haskell's difficulties in reasoning about lazy evaluation and in using traditional data structures such as mutable arrays.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] Robert Harper, one of the authors of Standard ML, has given his reasons for not using Haskell to teach introductory programming.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] Among these are the difficulty of reasoning about resource use with non-strict evaluation, that lazy evaluation complicates the definition of datatypes and inductive reasoning, and the "inferiority" of Haskell's (old) class system compared to ML's module system.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] Haskell's build tool, Cabal, has historically been criticized for poorly handling multiple versions of the same library, a problem known as "Cabal hell".
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] The Stackage server and Stack build tool were made in response to these criticisms.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] Cabal has since addressed this problem by borrowing ideas from the package manager Nix, with the new approach becoming the default in 2019.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] Clean is a close, slightly older relative of Haskell.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] Its biggest deviation from Haskell is in the use of uniqueness types instead of monads for input/output (I/O) and side effects.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] Haskell events have been regularly held concurrent with the International Conference on Functional Programming (ICFP) including workshops such as the Haskell Symposium (formerly the Haskell Workshop) and Commercial Users of Functional Programming.
[src:scotty-haskell/haskell] Other events include the Haskell Implementors Workshop, ZuriHac in Zurich, and Hac: The Haskell Hackathon.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] In functional programming, **monads** are a way to structure computations as a sequence of steps, where each step not only produces a value but also some extra information about the computation, such as a potential failure, non-determinism, or side effect.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] More formally, a monad is a type constructor M equipped with two operations, `return : <A>(a : A) -> M(A)` which lifts a value into the monadic context, and `bind : <A,B>(m_a : M(A), f : A -> M(B)) -> M(B)` which chains monadic computations.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] In simpler terms, monads can be thought of as interfaces implemented on type constructors, that allow for functions to abstract over various type constructor variants that implement monad (e.g.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Both the concept of a monad and the term originally come from category theory, where a monad is defined as an endofunctor with additional structure.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Research beginning in the late 1980s and early 1990s established that monads could bring seemingly disparate computer-science problems under a unified, functional model.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Category theory also provides a few formal requirements, known as the **monad laws**, which should be satisfied by any monad and can be used to verify monadic code.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Since monads make semantics explicit for a kind of computation, they can also be used to implement convenient language features.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Some languages, such as Haskell, even offer pre-built definitions in their core libraries for the general monad structure and common instances.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] "For a monad `m`, a value of type `m a` represents having access to a value of type `a` within the context of the monad." —C.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] More exactly, a monad can be used where unrestricted access to a value is inappropriate for reasons specific to the scenario.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] In the case of the Maybe monad, it is because the value may not exist.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] In the case of the IO monad, it is because the value may not be known yet, such as when the monad represents user input that will only be provided after a prompt is displayed.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] In all cases the scenarios in which access makes sense are captured by the bind operation defined for the monad; for the Maybe monad a value is bound only if it exists, and for the IO monad a value is bound only after the previous operations in the sequence have been performed.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] With these elements, the programmer composes a sequence of function calls (a "pipeline") with several *bind* operators chained together in an expression.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Each function call transforms its input plain-type value, and the bind operator handles the returned monadic value, which is fed into the next step in the sequence.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Typically, the bind operator `>>=` may contain code unique to the monad that performs additional computation steps not available in the function received as a parameter.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Between each pair of composed function calls, the bind operator can inject into the monadic value `m a` some additional information that is not accessible within the function `f`, and pass it along down the pipeline.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] It can also exert finer control of the flow of execution, for example by calling the function only under some conditions, or executing the function calls in a particular order.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] One example of a monad is the `Maybe` type.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Undefined null results are one particular pain point that many procedural languages don't provide specific tools for dealing with, requiring use of the null object pattern or checks to test for invalid values at each operation to handle undefined values.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] This causes bugs and makes it harder to build robust software that gracefully handles errors.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] The `Maybe` type forces the programmer to deal with these potentially undefined results by explicitly defining the two states of a result: `Just ⌑result⌑`, or `Nothing`.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] For example, the programmer might be constructing a parser, which is to return an intermediate result, or else signal a condition which the parser has detected, and which the programmer must also handle.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] With just a little extra functional spice on top, this `Maybe` type transforms into a fully-featured monad.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] In most languages, the Maybe monad is also known as an option type, which is just a type that marks whether or not it contains a value.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Typically they are expressed as some kind of enumerated type.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] In the Rust programming language it is called `Option<T>` and variants of this type can either be a value of generic type `T`, or the empty variant: `None`.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] `Option<T>` can also be understood as a "wrapping" type, and this is where its connection to monads comes in.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] In languages with some form of the Maybe type, there are functions that aid in their use such as composing **monadic functions** with each other and testing if a Maybe contains a value.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] In the following hard-coded example, a Maybe type is used as a result of functions that may fail, in this case the type returns nothing if there is a divide-by-zero.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] One such way to test whether or not a Maybe contains a value is to use `if` statements.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Monads can compose functions that return Maybe, putting them together.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Instead of repeating `Some` expressions, we can use something called a *bind* operator.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] (also known as "map", "flatmap", or "shove").
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] This operation takes a monad and a function that returns a monad and runs the function on the inner value of the passed monad, returning the monad from the function.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] In Haskell, there is an operator *bind*, or (`>>=`) that allows for this monadic composition in a more elegant form similar to function composition.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] With `>>=` available, `chainable_division` can be expressed much more succinctly with the help of anonymous functions (i.e. lambdas).
