[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] What has been shown so far is basically a monad, but to be more concise, the following is a strict list of qualities necessary for a monad as defined by the following section.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] These are the 3 things necessary to form a monad.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Other monads may embody different logical processes, and some may have additional properties, but all of them will have these three similar components.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] The more common definition for a monad in functional programming, used in the above example, is actually based on a Kleisli triple ⟨T, η, μ⟩ rather than category theory's standard definition.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] The two constructs turn out to be mathematically equivalent, however, so either definition will yield a valid monad.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Algebraically, this means any monad both gives rise to a category (called the Kleisli category) *and* a monoid in the category of functors (from values to computations), with monadic composition as a binary operator in the monoid and unit as identity in the monoid.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] The value of the monad pattern goes beyond merely condensing code and providing a link to mathematical reasoning.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Whatever language or default programming paradigm a developer uses, following the monad pattern brings many of the benefits of purely functional programming.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] By reifying a specific kind of computation, a monad not only encapsulates the tedious details of that computational pattern, but it does so in a declarative way, improving the code's clarity.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] As monadic values explicitly represent not only computed values, but computed *effects*, a monadic expression can be replaced with its value in referentially transparent positions, much like pure expressions can be, allowing for many techniques and optimizations based on rewriting.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Typically, programmers will use bind to chain monadic functions into a sequence, which has led some to describe monads as "programmable semicolons", a reference to how many imperative languages use semicolons to separate statements.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] However, monads do not actually order computations; even in languages that use them as central features, simpler function composition can arrange steps within a program.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] A monad's general utility rather lies in simplifying a program's structure and improving separation of concerns through abstraction.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] The monad structure can also be seen as a uniquely mathematical and compile time variation on the decorator pattern.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Some monads can pass along extra data that is inaccessible to functions, and some even exert finer control over execution, for example only calling a function under certain conditions.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Because they let application programmers implement domain logic while offloading boilerplate code onto pre-developed modules, monads can even be considered a tool for aspect-oriented programming.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] One other noteworthy use for monads is isolating side-effects, like input/output or mutable state, in otherwise purely functional code.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Even purely functional languages *can* still implement these "impure" computations without monads, via an intricate mix of function composition and continuation-passing style (CPS) in particular.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] With monads though, much of this scaffolding can be abstracted away, essentially by taking each recurring pattern in CPS code and bundling it into a distinct monad.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] If a language does not support monads by default, it is still possible to implement the pattern, often without much difficulty.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] When translated from category-theory to programming terms, the monad structure is a generic concept and can be defined directly in any language that supports an equivalent feature for bounded polymorphism.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] A concept's ability to remain agnostic about operational details while working on underlying types is powerful, but the unique features and stringent behavior of monads set them apart from other concepts.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Discussions of specific monads will typically focus on solving a narrow implementation problem since a given monad represents a specific computational form.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] In some situations though, an application can even meet its high-level goals by using appropriate monads within its core logic.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] The term "monad" in programming dates to the APL and J programming languages, which do tend toward being purely functional.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] However, in those languages, "monad" is only shorthand for a function taking one parameter (a function with two parameters being a "dyad", and so on).
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] The mathematician Roger Godement was the first to formulate the concept of a monad (dubbing it a "standard construction") in the late 1950s, though the term "monad" that came to dominate was popularized by category-theorist Saunders Mac Lane.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] The form defined above using bind, however, was originally described in 1965 by mathematician Heinrich Kleisli in order to prove that any monad could be characterized as an adjunction between two (covariant) functors.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Starting in the 1980s, a vague notion of the monad pattern began to surface in the computer science community.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] According to programming language researcher Philip Wadler, computer scientist John C.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Reynolds anticipated several facets of it in the 1970s and early 1980s, when he discussed the value of continuation-passing style, of category theory as a rich source for formal semantics, and of the type distinction between values and computations.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] The research language Opal, which was actively designed up until 1990, also effectively based I/O on a monadic type, but the connection was not realized at the time.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] The computer scientist Eugenio Moggi was the first to explicitly link the monad of category theory to functional programming, in a conference paper in 1989, followed by a more refined journal submission in 1991.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] In earlier work, several computer scientists had advanced using category theory to provide semantics for the lambda calculus.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Moggi's key insight was that a real-world program is not just a function from values to other values, but rather a transformation that forms *computations* on those values.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] When formalized in category-theoretic terms, this leads to the conclusion that monads are the structure to represent these computations.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Several others popularized and built on this idea, including Philip Wadler and Simon Peyton Jones, both of whom were involved in the specification of Haskell.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] In particular, Haskell used a problematic "lazy stream" model up through v1.2 to reconcile I/O with lazy evaluation, until switching over to a more flexible monadic interface.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] The Haskell community would go on to apply monads to many problems in functional programming, and in the 2010s, researchers working with Haskell eventually recognized that monads are applicative functors; and that both monads and arrows are monoids.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] At first, programming with monads was largely confined to Haskell and its derivatives, but as functional programming has influenced other paradigms, many languages have incorporated a monad pattern (in spirit if not in name).
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Formulations now exist in Scheme, Perl, Python, Racket, Clojure, Scala, F#, and have also been considered for a new ML standard.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] One benefit of the monad pattern is bringing mathematical precision on the composition of computations.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Not only can the monad laws be used to check an instance's validity, but features from related structures (like functors) can be used through subtyping.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Returning to the `Maybe` example, its components were declared to make up a monad, but no proof was given that it satisfies the monad laws.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Though rarer in computer science, one can use category theory directly, which defines a monad as a functor with two additional natural transformations.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] This is not always a major issue, however, especially when a monad is derived from a pre-existing functor, whereupon the monad inherits map automatically.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] A monad's first transformation is actually the same unit from the Kleisli triple, but following the hierarchy of structures closely, it turns out unit characterizes an applicative functor, an intermediate structure between a monad and a basic functor.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] In the applicative context, unit is sometimes referred to as **pure** but is still the same function.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] The **List monad** naturally demonstrates how deriving a monad from a simpler functor can come in handy.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] In many languages, a list structure comes pre-defined along with some basic features, so a `List` type constructor and append operator (represented with `++` for infix notation) are assumed as already given here.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] From here, applying a function iteratively with a list comprehension may seem like an easy choice for bind and converting lists to a full monad.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] The difficulty with this approach is that bind expects monadic functions, which in this case will output lists themselves; as more functions are applied, layers of nested lists will accumulate, requiring more than a basic comprehension.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Now, these two procedures already promote `List` to an applicative functor.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] One application for this monadic list is representing nondeterministic computation.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] `List` can hold results for all execution paths in an algorithm, then condense itself at each step to "forget" which paths led to which results (a sometimes important distinction from deterministic, exhaustive algorithms).
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Another benefit is that checks can be embedded in the monad; specific paths can be pruned transparently at their first point of failure, with no need to rewrite functions in the pipeline.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] A second situation where `List` shines is composing multivalued functions.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] For instance, the nth complex root of a number should yield n distinct complex numbers, but if another mth root is then taken of those results, the final m•n values should be identical to the output of the m•nth root.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] `List` completely automates this issue away, condensing the results from each step into a flat, mathematically correct list.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Monads present opportunities for interesting techniques beyond just organizing program logic.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Monads can lay the groundwork for useful syntactic features while their high-level and mathematical nature enable significant abstraction.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Although using bind openly often makes sense, many programmers prefer a syntax that mimics imperative statements (called *do-notation* in Haskell, *perform-notation* in OCaml, *computation expressions* in F#, and *for comprehension* in Scala).
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] This is only syntactic sugar that disguises a monadic pipeline as a code block; the compiler will then quietly translate these expressions into underlying functional code.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Translating the `add` function from the `Maybe` into Haskell can show this feature in action.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] A second example shows how `Maybe` can be used in an entirely different language: F#.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Every monad needs a specific implementation that meets the monad laws, but other aspects like the relation to other structures or standard idioms within a language are shared by all monads.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] As a result, a language or library may provide a general `Monad` interface with function prototypes, subtyping relationships, and other general facts.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Besides providing a head-start to development and guaranteeing a new monad inherits features from a supertype (such as functors), checking a monad's design against the interface adds another layer of quality control.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Monadic code can often be simplified even further through the judicious use of operators.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] The map functional can be especially helpful since it works on more than just ad-hoc monadic functions; so long as a monadic function should work analogously to a predefined operator, map can be used to instantly "lift" the simpler operator into a monadic one.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] The process could be taken even one step further by defining `add` not just for `Maybe`, but for the whole `Monad` interface.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] By doing this, any new monad that matches the structure interface and implements its own map will immediately inherit a lifted version of `add` too.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] `Identity` does actually have valid uses though, such as providing a base case for recursive monad transformers.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] It can also be used to perform basic variable assignment within an imperative-style block.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Any collection with a proper append is already a monoid, but it turns out that `List` is not the only collection that also has a well-defined join and qualifies as a monad.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] As already mentioned, pure code should not have unmanaged side effects, but that does not preclude a program from *explicitly* describing and managing effects.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] This idea is central to Haskell's **IO monad**, where an object of type `IO a` can be seen as describing an action to be performed in the world, optionally providing information about the world of type `a`.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] An action that provides no information about the world has the type `IO ()`, "providing" the dummy value `()`.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] When a programmer binds an `IO` value to a function, the function computes the next action to be performed based on the information about the world provided by the previous action (input from users, files, etc.).
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Most significantly, because the value of the IO monad can only be bound to a function that computes another IO monad, the bind function imposes a discipline of a sequence of actions where the result of an action can only be provided to a function that will compute the next action to perform.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] This means that actions which do not need to be performed never are, and actions that do need to be performed have a well defined sequence.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] For example, Haskell has several functions for acting on the wider file system, including one that checks whether a file exists and another that deletes a file.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] The first is interested in whether a given file really exists, and as a result, outputs a Boolean value within the `IO` monad.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] The second function, on the other hand, is only concerned with acting on the file system so the `IO` container it outputs is empty.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Another common situation is keeping a log file or otherwise reporting a program's progress.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Sometimes, a programmer may want to log even more specific, technical data for later profiling or debugging.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] The **Writer monad** can handle these tasks by generating auxiliary output that accumulates step-by-step.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] To show how the monad pattern is not restricted to primarily functional languages, this example implements a `Writer` monad in Java, stored in a class representing the `Writer` monad.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] An environment monad (also called a *reader monad* and a *function monad*) allows a computation to depend on values from a shared environment.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] The monad type constructor maps a type T to functions of type *E* → *T*, where E is the type of the shared environment.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] The ask operation is used to retrieve the current context, while local executes a computation in a modified subcontext.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] As in a state monad, computations in the environment monad may be invoked by simply providing an environment value and applying it to an instance of the monad.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Formally, a value in an environment monad is equivalent to a function with an additional, anonymous argument; return and bind are equivalent to the K and S combinators, respectively, in the SKI combinator calculus.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] A state monad allows a programmer to attach state information of any type to a calculation.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Given any value type, the corresponding type in the state monad is a function which accepts a state, then outputs a new state (of type `s`) along with a return value (of type `t`).
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] This is similar to an environment monad, except that it also returns a new state, and thus allows modeling a *mutable* environment.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Note that this monad takes a type parameter, the type of the state information.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] do-blocks in a state monad are sequences of operations that can examine and update the state data.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Informally, a state monad of state type S maps the type of return values T into functions of type $S\rightarrow T\times S$ , where S is the underlying state.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] From the category theory point of view, a state monad is derived from the adjunction between the product functor and the exponential functor, which exists in any cartesian closed category by definition.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] A continuation monad with return type R maps type T into functions of type $\left(T\rightarrow R\right)\rightarrow R$ .
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] It is used to model continuation-passing style.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] That is, both functions take in an integer and return another integer.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Where the result is the result of `foo` applied to the result of `bar` applied to `x`.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] But suppose we are debugging our program, and we would like to add logging messages to `foo` and `bar`.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] So that both functions return a tuple, with the result of the application as the integer, and a logging message with information about the applied function and all the previously applied functions as the string.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Unfortunately, this means we can no longer compose `foo` and `bar`, as their input type `int` is not compatible with their output type `int * string`.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] And although we can again gain composability by modifying the types of each function to be `int * string -> int * string`, this would require us to add boilerplate code to each function to extract the integer from the tuple, which would get tedious as the number of such functions increases.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] `bind` takes in an integer and string tuple, then takes in a function (like `foo`) that maps from an integer to an integer and string tuple.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Its output is an integer and string tuple, which is the result of applying the input function to the integer within the input integer and string tuple.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] In this way, we only need to write boilerplate code to extract the integer from the tuple once, in `bind`.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Now we have regained some composability.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Where `(x,s)` is an integer and string tuple.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] So that `t >>= f` is the same as `bind t f`.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Finally, we define a new function to avoid writing `(x, "")` every time we wish to create an empty logging message, where `""` is the empty string.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Which wraps `x` in the tuple described above.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] That allows us to more easily log the effects of `bar` and `foo` on `x`.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] `int * string` denotes a pseudo-coded **monadic value**.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] `bind` and `return` are analogous to the corresponding functions of the same name.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] In fact, `int * string`, `bind`, and `return` form a monad.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] An **additive monad** is a monad endowed with an additional closed, associative, binary operator **mplus** and an identity element under mplus, called **mzero**.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] The `Maybe` monad can be considered additive, with `Nothing` as mzero and a variation on the OR operator as mplus.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] `List` is also an additive monad, with the empty list `[]` acting as mzero and the concatenation operator `++` as mplus.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Intuitively, mzero represents a monadic wrapper with no value from an underlying type, but is also considered a "zero" (rather than a "one") since it acts as an absorber for bind, returning mzero whenever bound to a monadic function.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] This property is two-sided, and bind will also return mzero when any value is bound to a monadic zero function.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] In category-theoretic terms, an additive monad qualifies once as a monoid over monadic functions with bind (as all monads do), and again over monadic values via mplus.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Sometimes, the general outline of a monad may be useful, but no simple pattern recommends one monad or another.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] This is where a **free monad** comes in; as a free object in the category of monads, it can represent monadic structure without any specific constraints beyond the monad laws themselves.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Just as a free monoid concatenates elements without evaluation, a free monad allows chaining computations with markers to satisfy the type system, but otherwise imposes no deeper semantics itself.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] For example, by working entirely through the `Just` and `Nothing` markers, the `Maybe` monad is in fact a free monad.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] The `List` monad, on the other hand, is not a free monad since it brings extra, specific facts about lists (like append) into its definition.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Free monads, however, are *not* restricted to a linked-list like in this example, and can be built around other structures like trees.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Using free monads intentionally may seem impractical at first, but their formal nature is particularly well-suited for syntactic problems.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] A free monad can be used to track syntax and type while leaving semantics for later, and has found use in parsers and interpreters as a result.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Others have applied them to more dynamic, operational problems too, such as providing iteratees within a language.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Besides generating monads with extra properties, for any given monad, one can also define a **comonad**.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Conceptually, if monads represent computations built up from underlying values, then comonads can be seen as reductions back down to values.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Monadic code, in a sense, cannot be fully "unpacked"; once a value is wrapped within a monad, it remains quarantined there along with any side-effects (a good thing in purely functional programming).
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Sometimes though, a problem is more about consuming contextual data, which comonads can model explicitly.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Technically, a comonad is the categorical dual of a monad, which loosely means that it will have the same required components, only with the direction of the type signatures *reversed*.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] While operations like extend are reversed, however, a comonad does *not* reverse functions it acts on, and consequently, comonads are still functors with map, not cofunctors.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] A simple example is the **Product comonad**, which outputs values based on an input value and shared environment data.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] In fact, the `Product` comonad is just the dual of the `Writer` monad and effectively the same as the `Reader` monad (both discussed below).
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] `Product` and `Reader` differ only in which function signatures they accept, and how they complement those functions by wrapping or unwrapping values.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] A less trivial example is the **Stream comonad**, which can be used to represent data streams and attach filters to the incoming signals with extend.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] In fact, while not as popular as monads, researchers have found comonads particularly useful for stream processing and modeling dataflow programming.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] Due to their strict definitions, however, one cannot simply move objects back and forth between monads and comonads.
[src:scotty-haskell/monad-functional-programming] As an even higher abstraction, arrows can subsume both structures, but finding more granular ways to combine monadic and comonadic code is an active area of research.
[src:scotty-haskell/package-scotty] A Haskell web framework inspired by Ruby's Sinatra, using WAI and Warp.
[src:scotty-haskell/package-scotty] Scotty is the cheap and cheerful way to write RESTful, declarative web applications.
[src:scotty-haskell/package-scotty] As for the name: Sinatra + Warp = Scotty.
[src:scotty-haskell/package-scotty] Additionally, the `examples` directory shows a number of concrete use cases, e.g.
[src:scotty-haskell/package-scotty] Tutorials and related projects can be found in the Scotty wiki.
[src:scotty-haskell/package-scotty] Feel free to ask questions or report bugs on the Github issue tracker.
[src:scotty-haskell/package-scotty] Scotty adheres to the Package Versioning Policy.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] In packet switching networks, routing is the higher-level decision-making that directs network packets from their source toward their destination through intermediate network nodes by specific packet forwarding mechanisms.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Packet forwarding is the transit of network packets from one network interface to another.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Intermediate nodes are typically network hardware devices such as routers, gateways, firewalls, or switches.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] General-purpose computers also forward packets and perform routing, although they have no specially optimized hardware for the task.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] The routing process usually directs forwarding on the basis of routing tables.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Routing tables maintain a record of the routes to various network destinations.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Routing tables may be specified by an administrator, learned by observing network traffic or built with the assistance of routing protocols.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Routing, in a narrower sense of the term, often refers to IP routing and is contrasted with bridging.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] IP routing assumes that network addresses are structured and that similar addresses imply proximity within the network.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Structured addresses allow a single routing table entry to represent the route to a group of devices.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] In large networks, structured addressing (routing, in the narrow sense) outperforms unstructured addressing (bridging).
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Routing has become the dominant form of addressing on the Internet.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Bridging is still widely used within local area networks.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Unicast is the dominant form of message delivery on the Internet.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] This article focuses on unicast routing algorithms.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] With static routing, small networks may use manually configured routing tables.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Larger networks have complex topologies that can change rapidly, making the manual construction of routing tables unfeasible.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Nevertheless, most of the public switched telephone network (PSTN) uses pre-computed routing tables, with fallback routes if the most direct route becomes blocked (see routing in the PSTN).
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Dynamic routing attempts to solve this problem by constructing routing tables automatically, based on information carried by routing protocols, allowing the network to act nearly autonomously in avoiding network failures and blockages.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Examples of dynamic-routing protocols and algorithms include Routing Information Protocol (RIP), Open Shortest Path First (OSPF) and Enhanced Interior Gateway Routing Protocol (EIGRP).
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Distance vector algorithms use the Bellman–Ford algorithm.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] This approach assigns a *cost* number to each of the links between each node in the network.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Nodes send information from point A to point B via the path that results in the lowest *total cost* (i.e., the sum of the costs of the links between the nodes used).
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] When a node first starts, it only knows of its immediate neighbors and the direct cost involved in reaching them.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] The neighboring nodes examine this information and compare it to what they already know; anything that represents an improvement on what they already have, they insert in their own table.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Over time, all the nodes in the network discover the best next hop and total cost for all destinations.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] When a network node goes down, any nodes that used it as their next hop discard the entry and convey the updated routing information to all adjacent nodes, which in turn repeat the process.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Eventually, all the nodes in the network receive the updates and discover new paths to all the destinations that do not involve the down node.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] When applying link-state algorithms, a graphical map of the network is the fundamental data used for each node.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] To produce its map, each node floods the entire network with information about the other nodes it can connect to.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Each node then independently assembles this information into a map.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Using this map, each router independently determines the least-cost path from itself to every other node using a standard shortest paths algorithm such as Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] The result is a tree graph rooted at the current node, such that the path through the tree from the root to any other node is the least-cost path to that node.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] This tree then serves to construct the routing table, which specifies the best next hop to get from the current node to any other node.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] A link-state routing algorithm optimized for mobile ad hoc networks is the optimized Link State Routing Protocol (OLSR).
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] OLSR is proactive; it uses Hello and Topology Control (TC) messages to discover and disseminate link-state information through the mobile ad hoc network.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Using Hello messages, each node discovers 2-hop neighbor information and elects a set of *multipoint relays* (MPRs).
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] MPRs distinguish OLSR from other link-state routing protocols.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Distance vector and link-state routing are both intra-domain routing protocols.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] They are used inside an autonomous system, but not between autonomous systems.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Both of these routing protocols become intractable in large networks and cannot be used in inter-domain routing.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Distance vector routing is subject to instability if there are more than a few hops in the domain.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Link-state routing needs significant resources to calculate routing tables.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] It also creates heavy traffic due to flooding.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Path-vector routing is used for inter-domain routing.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] It is similar to distance vector routing.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Path-vector routing assumes that one node (there can be many) in each autonomous system acts on behalf of the entire autonomous system.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] This node is called the *speaker node.* The speaker node creates a routing table and advertises it to neighboring speaker nodes in neighboring autonomous systems.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] The idea is the same as distance vector routing, except that only speaker nodes in each autonomous system can communicate with each other.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] The speaker node advertises the path, not the metric, of the nodes in its autonomous system or other autonomous systems.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] The path-vector routing algorithm is similar to the distance vector algorithm in the sense that each border router advertises the destinations it can reach to its neighboring router.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] However, instead of advertising networks in terms of a destination and the distance to that destination, networks are advertised as destination addresses and path descriptions to reach those destinations.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] The path, expressed in terms of the domains (or confederations) traversed so far, is carried in a special path attribute that records the sequence of routing domains through which the reachability information has passed.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] A route is defined as a pairing between a destination and the attributes of the path to that destination, thus the name, path-vector routing.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] The routers receive a vector that contains paths to a set of destinations.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Path selection involves applying a routing metric to multiple routes to select (or predict) the best route.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Most routing algorithms use only one network path at a time.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Multipath routing and specifically equal-cost multi-path routing techniques enable the use of multiple alternative paths.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] In computer networking, the metric is computed by a routing algorithm, and can cover information such as bandwidth, network delay, hop count, path cost, load, maximum transmission unit, reliability, and communication cost.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] The routing table stores only the best possible routes, while link-state or topological databases may store all other information as well.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] *Metric*: When comparing routes learned via the same routing protocol, a lower metric is preferred.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Metrics cannot be compared between routes learned from different routing protocols.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] *Administrative distance*: When comparing route table entries from different sources, such as different routing protocols and static configuration, a lower administrative distance indicates a more reliable source and thus a preferred route.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Because a routing metric is specific to a given routing protocol, multi-protocol routers must use some external heuristic to select between routes learned from different routing protocols.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Cisco routers, for example, attribute a value known as the administrative distance to each route, where smaller administrative distances indicate routes learned from a protocol assumed to be more reliable.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] A local administrator can set up host-specific routes that provide more control over network usage, permit testing, and better overall security.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] This is useful for debugging network connections or routing tables.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] In some small systems, a single central device decides ahead of time the complete path of every packet.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] In some other small systems, whichever edge device injects a packet into the network decides ahead of time the complete path of that particular packet.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] In either case, the route-planning device needs to know a lot of information about what devices are connected to the network and how they are connected to each other.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Once it has this information, it can use an algorithm such as A* search algorithm to find the best path.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] In high-speed systems, there are so many packets transmitted every second that it is infeasible for a single device to calculate the complete path for each and every packet.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Early high-speed systems dealt with this with circuit switching by setting up a path once for the first packet between some source and some destination; later packets between that same source and that same destination continue to follow the same path without recalculating until the circuit teardown.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Later high-speed systems inject packets into the network without any one device ever calculating a complete path for packets.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] In large systems, there are so many connections between devices, and those connections change so frequently, that it is infeasible for any one device to even know how all the devices are connected to each other, much less calculate a complete path through them.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Such systems generally use next-hop routing.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Most systems use a deterministic dynamic routing algorithm.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] When a device chooses a path to a particular final destination, that device always chooses the same path to that destination until it receives information that makes it think some other path is better.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] A few routing algorithms do not use a deterministic algorithm to find the best link for a packet to get from its original source to its final destination.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Instead, to avoid congestion hot spots in packet systems, a few algorithms use a randomized algorithm—Valiant's paradigm—that routes a path to a randomly picked intermediate destination, and from there to its true final destination.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] In many early telephone switches, a randomizer was often used to select the start of a path through a multistage switching fabric.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Depending on the application for which path selection is performed, different metrics can be used.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] For example, for web requests, one can use minimum latency paths to minimize web page load time, or for bulk data transfers, one can choose the least utilized path to balance load across the network and increase throughput.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] A popular path selection objective is to reduce the average completion times of traffic flows and the total network bandwidth consumption.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Recently, a path selection metric was proposed that computes the total number of bytes scheduled on the edges per path as a selection metric.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] An empirical analysis of several path selection metrics, including this new proposal, has been made available.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] In some networks, routing is complicated by the fact that no single entity is responsible for selecting paths; instead, multiple entities are involved in selecting paths or even parts of a single path.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Complications or inefficiency can result if these entities choose paths to optimize their own objectives, which may conflict with the objectives of other participants.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] A classic example involves traffic in a road system, in which each driver picks a path that minimizes their travel time.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] With such routing, the equilibrium routes can be longer than optimal for all drivers.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] In particular, Braess's paradox shows that adding a new road can *lengthen* travel times for all drivers.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] In a single-agent model used, for example, for routing automated guided vehicles (AGVs) on a terminal, reservations are made for each vehicle to prevent simultaneous use of the same part of an infrastructure.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] This approach is also referred to as context-aware routing.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] The Internet is partitioned into autonomous systems (ASs) such as internet service providers (ISPs), each of which controls routes involving its network.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] First, AS-level paths are selected via the BGP protocol that produces a sequence of ASs through which packets flow.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Each AS may have multiple paths, offered by neighboring ASs, from which to choose.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] These routing decisions often correlate with business relationships with these neighboring ASs, which may be unrelated to path quality or latency.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Second, once an AS-level path has been selected, there are often multiple corresponding router-level paths to choose from.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] This is due, in part, because two ISPs may be connected through multiple connections.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] In choosing the single router-level path, it is common practice for each ISP to employ hot-potato routing: sending traffic along the path that minimizes the distance through the ISP's own network—even if that path lengthens the total distance to the destination.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] For example, consider two ISPs, *A* and *B*.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Each has a presence in New York, connected by a fast link with latency 5 ms—and each has a presence in London connected by a 5 ms link.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Suppose both ISPs have trans-Atlantic links that connect their two networks, but *A*'s link has latency 100 ms and *B*'s has latency 120 ms.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] When routing a message from a source in *A*'s London network to a destination in *B*'s New York network, *A* may choose to immediately send the message to *B* in London.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] This saves *A* the work of sending it along an expensive trans-Atlantic link, but causes the message to experience latency 125 ms when the other route would have been 20 ms faster.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Additionally, a similar routing challenge can be observed in cellular networks, where different packets are destined for various endpoints, and each link exhibits varying spectral efficiency.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] In this context, the selection of the *optimal* path involves considering latency and packet error rate.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] To address this, multiple independent entities, one for each base station, play a crucial role in path selection while striving to optimize overall network performance.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] A 2003 measurement study of Internet routes found that, between pairs of neighboring ISPs, more than 30% of paths have inflated latency due to hot-potato routing, with 5% of paths being delayed by at least 12 ms.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Inflation due to AS-level path selection, while substantial, was attributed primarily to BGP's lack of a mechanism to directly optimize for latency, rather than to selfish routing policies.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] It was also suggested that, were an appropriate mechanism in place, ISPs would be willing to cooperate to reduce latency rather than use hot-potato routing.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Such a mechanism was later published by the same authors, first for the case of two ISPs and then for the global case.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] As the Internet and IP networks have become mission critical business tools, there has been increased interest in techniques and methods to monitor the routing posture of networks.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Incorrect routing or routing issues cause undesirable performance degradation, flapping or downtime.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Monitoring routing in a network is achieved using route analytics tools and techniques.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] In networks where a logically centralized control is available over the forwarding state, for example, using software-defined networking, routing techniques can be used that aim to optimize global and network-wide performance metrics.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] This has been used by large internet companies that operate many data centers in different geographical locations attached using private optical links, examples of which include Microsoft's Global WAN, Facebook's Express Backbone, and Google's B4.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Global performance metrics to optimize include maximizing network utilization, minimizing traffic flow completion times, maximizing the traffic delivered prior to specific deadlines and reducing the completion times of flows.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] Work on the later over private WAN discusses modeling routing as a graph optimization problem by pushing all the queuing to the end-points.
[src:scotty-haskell/routing] The authors also propose a heuristic to solve the problem efficiently while sacrificing negligible performance.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] A **web framework** (**WF**), **web application framework** (**WAF**), or **web development framework** is a software framework that is designed to support the development of web applications including web services, web resources, and web APIs.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] Web frameworks provide a standard way to build and deploy web applications on the World Wide Web.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] Web frameworks aim to automate the overhead associated with common activities performed in web development.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] For example, many web frameworks provide libraries for database access, templating frameworks, and session management, and they often promote code reuse.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] Although they often target development of dynamic web sites, they are also applicable to static websites.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] As the design of the World Wide Web was not inherently dynamic, early hypertext consisted of hand-coded HTML text files that were published on web servers.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] Any modifications to published pages needed to be performed by the pages' author.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] In 1993, the Common Gateway Interface (CGI) standard was introduced for interfacing external applications with web servers, to provide a dynamic web page that reflected user inputs.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] Original implementations of the CGI interface typically had adverse effects on the server load however, because each request started a separate process.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] More recent implementations utilize persistent processes amongst other techniques to reduce the footprint in the server's resources and offer a general performance boost.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] In 1995, fully integrated server/language development environments first emerged and new web-specific languages were introduced, such as ColdFusion, PHP, and Active Server Pages.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] Although the vast majority of languages for creating dynamic web pages have libraries to help with common tasks, web applications often require specific libraries for particular tasks, such as creating HTML (for example, Jakarta Faces).
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] In the late 1990s, mature, "full stack" frameworks began to appear, that often gathered multiple libraries useful for web development into a single cohesive software stack for web developers to use.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] Most web frameworks are based on the model–view–controller (MVC) pattern.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] Many frameworks follow the MVC architectural pattern to separate the data model into business rules (the "controller") and the user interface (the "view").
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] This is generally considered a good practice as it modularizes code, promotes code reuse, and allows multiple interfaces to be applied.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] In web applications, this permits different views to be presented, for example serving different web pages for mobile vs. desktop browsers, or providing machine-readable web service interfaces.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] Most MVC frameworks follow a push-based architecture also called "action-based".
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] These frameworks use actions that do the required processing, and then "push" the data to the view layer to render the results.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] An alternative to this is pull-based architecture, sometimes also called "component-based".
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] These frameworks start with the view layer, which can then "pull" results from multiple controllers as needed.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] In this architecture, multiple controllers can be involved with a single view.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] In three-tier organization, applications are structured around three physical tiers: client, application, and database.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] The application contains the business logic, running on a server and communicates with the client using HTTP.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] The client on web applications is a web browser that runs HTML generated by the application layer.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] The term should not be confused with MVC, where, unlike in three-tier architecture, it is considered a good practice to keep business logic away from the controller, the "middle layer".
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] Web frameworks must function according to the architectural rules of browsers and protocols such as HTTP, which is stateless.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] Webpages are served up by a server and can then be modified by the browser using JavaScript.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] Either approach has its advantages and disadvantages.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] Server-side page changes typically require that the page be refreshed, but allow any language to be used and more computing power to be utilized.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] Client-side changes allow the page to be updated in small chunks which feels like a desktop application, but are limited to JavaScript and run in the user's browser, which may have limited computing power.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] Applications which make heavy use of JavaScript and only refresh parts of the page, are called single-page applications and typically make use of a client-side JavaScript web framework to organize the code.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] Examples include Backbone.js, AngularJS, Angular, Ember.js, ReactJS, jQuery UI, Svelte, and Vue.js.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] JavaScript-based web application frameworks, such as React and Vue, provide extensive capabilities but come with associated trade-offs.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] These frameworks often extend or enhance features available through native web technologies, such as routing, component-based development, and state management.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] Frameworks can introduce abstraction layers that may contribute to performance overhead, larger bundle sizes, and increased complexity.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] Modern frameworks, such as React 18 and Vue 3, address these challenges with features like concurrent rendering, tree-shaking, and selective hydration.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] While these advancements improve rendering efficiency and resource management, their benefits depend on the specific application and implementation context.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] Lightweight frameworks, such as Svelte and Preact, take different architectural approaches, with Svelte eliminating the virtual DOM entirely in favor of compiling components to efficient JavaScript code, and Preact offering a minimal, compatible alternative to React.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] Framework choice depends on an application’s requirements, including the team’s expertise, performance goals, and development priorities.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] A newer category of web frameworks, including enhance.dev, Astro, and Fresh, leverages native web standards while minimizing abstractions and development tooling.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] These solutions emphasize progressive enhancement, server-side rendering, and optimizing performance.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] Astro renders static HTML by default while hydrating only interactive parts.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] Fresh focuses on server-side rendering with zero runtime overhead.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] Enhance.dev prioritizes progressive enhancement patterns using Web Components.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] While these tools reduce reliance on client-side JavaScript by shifting logic to build-time or server-side execution, they still use JavaScript where necessary for interactivity.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] This approach makes them particularly suitable for performance-critical and content-focused applications.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] Frameworks typically set the control flow of a program and allow the user of the framework to "hook into" that flow by exposing various events.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] This "inversion of control" design pattern is considered to be a defining principle of a framework, and benefits the code by enforcing a common flow for a team which everyone can customize in similar ways.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] For example, some popular "microframeworks" such as Ruby's Sinatra (which inspired Express.js) allow for "middleware" hooks prior to and after HTTP requests.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] These middleware functions can be anything, and allow the user to define logging, authentication and session management, and redirecting.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] Web caching is the caching of web documents in order to reduce bandwidth usage, server load, and perceived "lag".
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] A web cache stores copies of documents passing through it; subsequent requests may be satisfied from the cache if certain conditions are met.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] Some application frameworks provide mechanisms for caching documents and bypassing various stages of the page's preparation, such as database access or template interpretation.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] Some web frameworks come with authentication and authorization frameworks, that enable the web server to identify the users of the application, and restrict access to functions based on some defined criteria.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] Drupal is one example that provides role-based access to pages, and provides a web-based interface for creating users and assigning them roles.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] Many web frameworks create a unified API to a database backend, enabling web applications to work with a variety of databases with no code changes, and allowing programmers to work with higher-level concepts.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] Additionally, some object-oriented frameworks contain mapping tools to provide object-relational mapping, which maps objects to tuples.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] Some frameworks minimize web application configuration through the use of introspection and/or following well-known conventions.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] For example, many Java frameworks use Hibernate as a persistence layer, which can generate a database schema at runtime capable of persisting the necessary information.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] This allows the application designer to design business objects without needing to explicitly define a database schema.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] Frameworks such as Ruby on Rails can also work in reverse, that is, define properties of model objects at runtime based on a database schema.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] Other features web frameworks may provide include transactional support and database migration tools.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] A framework's URL mapping or routing facility is the mechanism by which the framework interprets URLs.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] Some frameworks, such as Drupal and Django, match the provided URL against pre-determined patterns using regular expressions, while some others use rewriting techniques to translate the provided URL into one that the underlying engine will recognize.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] Another technique is that of graph traversal such as used by Zope, where a URL is decomposed in steps that traverse an object graph (of models and views).
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] A URL mapping system that uses pattern matching or rewriting to route and handle requests allows for shorter more "friendly URLs" to be used, increasing the simplicity of the site and allowing for better indexing by search engines.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] For example, a URL that ends with "/page.cgi?cat=science&topic=physics" could be changed to simply "/page/science/physics".
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] This makes the URL easier for people to remember, read and write, and provides search engines with better information about the structural layout of the site.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] A graph traversal approach also tends to result in the creation of friendly URLs.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] A shorter URL such as "/page/science" tends to exist by default as that is simply a shorter form of the longer traversal to "/page/science/physics".
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] Ajax, shorthand for "*Asynchronous JavaScript and XML*", is a web development technique for creating web applications.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] The intent is to make web pages feel more responsive by exchanging small amounts of data with the server behind the scenes, so that the entire web page does not have to be reloaded each time the user requests a change.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] This is intended to increase a web page's interactivity, speed, maintainability, and usability.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] Due to the complexity of Ajax programming in JavaScript, there are numerous Ajax frameworks that exclusively deal with Ajax support.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] Some Ajax frameworks are even embedded as a part of larger frameworks.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] For example, the jQuery JavaScript library is included in Ruby on Rails.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] With the increased interest in developing "Web 2.0" rich web applications, the complexity of programming directly in Ajax and JavaScript has become so apparent that compiler technology has stepped in, to allow developers to code in high-level languages such as Java, Python and Ruby.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] The first of these compilers was Morfik followed by Google Web Toolkit, with ports to Python and Ruby in the form of Pyjs and RubyJS following some time after.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] These compilers and their associated widget set libraries make the development of rich media Ajax applications much more akin to that of developing desktop applications.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] Some frameworks provide tools for creating and providing web services.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] These utilities may offer similar tools as the rest of the web application.
[src:scotty-haskell/web-framework] A number of newer Web 2.0 RESTful frameworks are now providing resource-oriented architecture (ROA) infrastructure for building collections of resources in a sort of Semantic Web ontology, based on concepts from Resource Description Framework (RDF).
